      "h": "Mexican Governance and Settler Relations",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texas was governed by Mexico but had a growing population of Anglo settlers who often clashed with Mexican laws and officials. These tensions over political control and cultural differences set the stage for conflict.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from en.wikipedia.org; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Mexico gained independence from Spain in 1821, inheriting Texas</li><li>Mexican government encouraged Anglo-American settlement to develop Texas</li><li>Tensions grew over laws, culture, and governance between settlers and Mexico</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Mexico’s 1830 law restricting immigration and enforcing customs duties angered many settlers.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Consider why Mexican authorities might have wanted to limit Anglo-American immigration.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming settlers had full autonomy or equal rights under Mexican law.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> en.wikipedia.org; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p>"
