      "h": "Centralism vs. Federalism: The Political Divide",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Political changes in Mexico, especially under President Santa Anna, intensified conflicts with Texas settlers who wanted more autonomy and respect for their customs.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from en.wikipedia.org; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Mexico’s shift to centralist government under Santa Anna alarmed Texans</li><li>Settlers opposed restrictions on immigration and local governance</li><li>Disputes over customs duties, language, and legal rights escalated</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>The 1835 closure of the Texas legislature by Mexican authorities sparked protests.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify how centralization of power can cause regional unrest.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Ignoring the role of Mexican political changes in causing the war.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> en.wikipedia.org; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p>"
