    "id": "slide11",
    "eyebrow": "Practice",
    "num": "11",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">11</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Practice</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Mapping the Players and Places</h2><ul><li>Identify key locations: San Antonio, Gonzales, San Jacinto</li><li>Match leaders to their roles and locations</li><li>Understand how geography influenced leadership decisions</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">This activity helps connect the people and places involved in the early Texas conflict, reinforcing understanding of how geography and leadership intersected. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> San Antonio was the site of the Alamo, defended by Travis, Bowie, and Crockett.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> On a blank map, label key locations and assign leaders to their areas of influence.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Confusing locations or assuming all battles happened in one place.</p></div></div>",
