      "h": "Why Geography Matters in Leadership",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This activity helps connect the people and places involved in the early Texas conflict, reinforcing understanding of how geography and leadership intersected.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from en.wikipedia.org; en.wikipedia.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Identify key locations: San Antonio, Gonzales, San Jacinto</li><li>Match leaders to their roles and locations</li><li>Understand how geography influenced leadership decisions</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>San Antonio was the site of the Alamo, defended by Travis, Bowie, and Crockett.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>On a blank map, label key locations and assign leaders to their areas of influence.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Confusing locations or assuming all battles happened in one place.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> en.wikipedia.org; en.wikipedia.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup></p>"
