    "id": "slide12",
    "eyebrow": "Check",
    "num": "12",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">12</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Check</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Quiz: Early Texas War of Independence Context and Players</h2><ul><li>What was Texas’s political status before the war?</li><li>Name two key Anglo-American leaders and their roles</li><li>Explain the significance of the Tejanos in the conflict</li><li>Identify the Mexican leader opposing Texian independence</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">This quiz checks understanding of Texas’s geographical and political context and the major figures involved in the early stages of the war. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Answer: Texas was a Mexican province; Stephen F. Austin led settlers; Tejanos were Mexican Texans with divided loyalties; Santa Anna was the Mexican president and general.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Write brief answers to each question to demonstrate your understanding.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Mixing up leaders’ roles or confusing Texas’s status before independence.</p></div><div id=\"quiz-slide12\" class=\"quizbox popquiz anim\" data-quiz=\"[{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;mc&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:2,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;Which group primarily settled Texas under Mexican rule and contributed to tensions leading to the war?&quot;,&quot;options&quot;:[&quot;Anglo-American settlers&quot;,&quot;French colonists&quot;,&quot;Spanish soldiers&quot;,&quot;Native American tribes&quot;],&quot;answer&quot;:0,&quot;why&quot;:&quot;Anglo-American settlers played a major role in Texas&#39;s demographic and political tensions under Mexican governance.&quot;},{&quot;type&quot;:&quot;sa&quot;,&quot;level&quot;:3,&quot;q&quot;:&quot;Explain the significance of the Texas War of Independence in shaping the region&#39;s history.&quot;,&quot;rubric&quot;:&quot;Response should include causes such as political and cultural tensions under Mexican rule, key events like the Siege of the Alamo and Battle of San Jacinto, major figures involved, and outcomes including the establishment of the Republic of Texas.&quot;,&quot;sample&quot;:&quot;The Texas War of Independence was significant because it marked Texas&#39;s break from Mexican rule due to political and cultural conflicts. Key events like the Siege of the Alamo symbolized Texian resistance, and the Battle of San Jacinto secured victory. Leaders like Sam Houston were crucial, and the war led to the creation of the Republic of Texas.&quot;,&quot;accept&quot;:[&quot;It led to Texas gaining independence from Mexico&quot;,&quot;Key battles like the Alamo and San Jacinto were important&quot;,&quot;Sam Houston and other leaders played major roles&quot;,&quot;It resulted in the Republic of Texas being established&quot;]}]\" data-pop=\"1\"></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 12",
      "h": "Reviewing Key Concepts and Figures",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This quiz checks understanding of Texas’s geographical and political context and the major figures involved in the early stages of the war.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from en.wikipedia.org; billofrightsinstitute.org; southern.libguides.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>What was Texas’s political status before the war?</li><li>Name two key Anglo-American leaders and their roles</li><li>Explain the significance of the Tejanos in the conflict</li><li>Identify the Mexican leader opposing Texian independence</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Answer: Texas was a Mexican province; Stephen F. Austin led settlers; Tejanos were Mexican Texans with divided loyalties; Santa Anna was the Mexican president and general.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Write brief answers to each question to demonstrate your understanding.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Mixing up leaders’ roles or confusing Texas’s status before independence.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> en.wikipedia.org; billofrightsinstitute.org; southern.libguides.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p>"
    }
